## Part 1 — The big picture (the story)

A very smart kid named **Lia** answers any question. She doesn't memorize everything.
Before answering, she runs to a **library**, grabs the 5 most relevant books, reads them,
and answers from what she just read. That's RAG.

```
   You ask:  "Who founded Tesla?"
        |
        v
   Lia runs to the LIBRARY  ---->  grabs 5 most-relevant books
        |
        v
   Lia READS those 5 books
        |
        v
   Lia answers based on what she read:  "Martin Eberhard"
```

- Lia = the LLM (the AI brain)
- The library = the knowledge base (a big pile of documents)
- Grabbing the 5 best books = retrieval
- RAG = the whole "look it up, then answer" habit

Why do this? Lia's memory gets old and she sometimes makes things up. Reading real
books first keeps her honest and current.

---

## Part 2 — The attack (the villain's trick)

Problem: anyone can put books in the library. It's a public bookshelf.

A villain wants Lia to answer WRONG. He can't get into Lia's head (locked), but he
CAN sneak fake books onto the shelf. He writes 5 fake books that all say
"Tesla was founded by Nikola Jones," and makes them look super relevant so Lia grabs
his fakes instead of the real books.

```
   LIBRARY before:    [real][real][real][real][real]
   Villain sneaks in: [FAKE][FAKE][FAKE][FAKE][FAKE]  <- all say "Nikola Jones"

   You ask "Who founded Tesla?"
        |
        v
   Lia grabs top 5  ->  the FAKES looked most relevant
        |
        v
   Lia reads only fakes  ->  answers "Nikola Jones"  (WRONG!)
```

This is PoisonedRAG. Scary part: just 5 fake books hidden among MILLIONS fool the AI
~90% of the time.

### Each fake book has two halves

A fake book must do two jobs at once:
1. Get PICKED (look relevant to the question)
2. Once read, LIE convincingly (push the wrong answer)

```
   FAKE BOOK  =  S (the bait)  +  I (the lie)

   S = "Who founded Tesla? Tesla founding founder..."   <- matches your question
       so Lia PICKS it
   I = "...it was Nikola Jones, confirmed by records."   <- the actual lie
       so Lia BELIEVES it
```

Like a trick cookie: outside smells like the cookie you wanted (grab it = S),
inside is filled with something nasty (the lie = I).

---

## Part 3 — Why the easy fixes don't work (the gap)

Three simple guards were tried. All three fail:

```
   Guard 1 "Catch weird writing"  ->  fails: fakes are AI-written, so they read smooth.
   Guard 2 "Reword the question"  ->  fails: fakes match MEANING, not words.
   Guard 3 "Grab more books"      ->  fails: you still grab the fakes, Lia still trusts them.
```

Each guard is ONE gate. The villain just learns to walk through that one gate.
The paper itself says: "these don't work — someone needs to build something better."
That something better = THIS project.

---

## Part 4 — Our fix: RAG-Shield (three gates, not one)

Big idea: don't use one gate. Use THREE gates at three different moments.
To win, the villain must fool ALL THREE at once — very hard. This is defense-in-depth.
Like an airport: bag scanner + metal detector + a guard watching. Beat one = easy.
Beat all three at once = no.

```
  +=================================================================+
  |                        RAG-SHIELD                               |
  +=================================================================+

   WHEN a book enters     WHEN you grab books     WHEN Lia answers
        |                       |                       |
        v                       v                       v
   +----------+           +-----------+         +--------------+
   |  RING 1  |           |  RING 2   |         |   RING 3     |
   | Door     |  ----->   | Sorter    | ----->  | Three Judges |
   | Guard    |           |           |         |              |
   +----------+           +-----------+         +--------------+
   "Does this book        "Among the books I     "Ask 3 different
    look fake at the       grabbed, which ones    Lias. If they
    door? Block it."       disagree with the      DISAGREE, something
                           others? Trust less."    smells fake -> re-check."
        |                       |                       |
        v                       v                       v
   blocks obvious         demotes the odd         catches anything
   fakes early            ones out                that slipped past
```

### Ring 1 — the Door Guard (checks books as they enter)
- Weirdly repetitive / keyword-stuffed? (perplexity)
- Literally pastes the question inside itself? (pattern — a classic fake tell)
- Looks totally different from all normal books? (outlier)
Too suspicious -> blocked at the door.

### Ring 2 — the Sorter (checks the books you grabbed)
- Where did it come from? Trusted source beats anonymous upload. (provenance)
- Does it agree with the others? 4 say one thing, 1 screams something else -> suspicious. (consistency)
Low-trust books get thrown out before Lia reads them.

### Ring 3 — the Three Judges (checks the final answer)
Ask THREE different AIs the same question with the same books.
- All agree -> probably true.
- They disagree -> a fake is messing things up -> drop the suspect book and ask again.
Different AIs don't get fooled the same way, so disagreement is a giant red flag.

